oleplaying. ow do you roleplay? what is so special about it <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ueannyarah.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eannyarah</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#CC9900>(9/7/01 1:32:47 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.brellserilis.net/images/posticons/luclintr.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: question</span><hr size=1> Roleplaying.  What is it?  What is the purpose, the meaning?  I would liken it to an actor's passion for his craft.  In essence it is the same.  Often times, the actor is such because he desires to convince others (and perhaps himself) that he's someone he's not.  Under this newfound guise, he can do things never before possible, he can say things he's never dare say, and he can be that which he could never before be.  Sometimes this is spawned by a growing dissatisfaction with the way things are, sometimes by a need to escape reality because of painful memories.  I act, and can testify that these reasons are all very valid and very powerful things acting on the very fabric of our souls.  When I'm on stage, or merely convincing people I am who I'm not for the sheer thrill of it, I can put aside who I am, and try to discover who I've become.  I can distance myself from my feelings, and sometimes even from my surroundings.  I can escape feelings of helplessness and hurt.  I can step out of the role that life has cast me in, and assume a new one, a new persona, form, being.  This is the inner essence of what roleplaying is.  It is escape.  It is experiencing dangers and perils not normally available.  It is a way to see who you really are, and who you're not, and what you're capable of being.  I hope I've answered your questions, friend.<br>
<br>
